; forget-stale.form — COMPOSTING: a prototype that never wins recognition over many queries is dead weight; drop it.
;
; THE ASK:
;   nearest-shape.form names the smallest act of LEARNING — interning a prototype the body had not seen, so
;   an unknown shape becomes recognizable. But a memory that only ever grows calcifies: every interned
;   prototype takes room in the recognition set forever, including the ones that turned out to recognize
;   nothing. The body needs the inverse breath — the smallest act of FORGETTING. Not "delete the least
;   recently used" (that punishes the rare-but-true), and not a graded decay (that needs a rate and a float).
;   The honest question is sharper: which prototypes have had a FAIR CHANCE to prove their worth and still
;   never (or almost never) won? Those, and only those, are sediment. forget-stale is that gate.
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/forget-stale.fk · proven: tests/forget-stale-band.fk -> 127, four-way)
;
;   A record = (list label wins age): the prototype's name, how many queries it has won, and how many total
;   queries have passed since it was interned (its age — the chances it has HAD to win). wins, age are
;   integers 0..100; label is a string (str_eq only, never crossed with eq).
;     fs-wins        (nth r 1) — times this prototype was the recognized best.
;     fs-age         (nth r 2) — total queries seen since interning (the denominator of opportunity, as a count).
;     fs-stale?      age >= min-age (old enough to judge) AND max-wins >= wins (too few wins) : both must hold.
;     fs-keep?       the exact inverse — young, OR proven by winning, is held onto.
;     fs-count-stale walk the records, count the dead weight (recursion is the loop).
;   The verdict is TWO integer comparisons joined by a binary and — no subtraction, no win-RATE (that would
;   need division), no float. A win-rate would ask "wins per age"; instead we gate the two counts directly,
;   so Go, Rust, and TS call the same prototype stale by NodeID. validate.sh parity is forgetting parity.
;
; HOW IT COMPOSES THE TOOLKIT:
;   it is nearest-shape.form's inverse — interning admits one prototype to LEARN; forget-stale drops one to
;   COMPOST, the smallest possible act of forgetting. The shape is classifier-eval.form's pass-gate, inverted:
;   classifier-eval PASSES a classifier on (enough correct AND few enough wrong); forget-stale DROPS a
;   prototype on (old enough AND few enough wins) — the same division-free two-count gate, pointed at memory
;   hygiene instead of promotion. Downstream of recognition-router.form: the router emits which model/prototype
;   WON each query; tallying those wins against each prototype's age is exactly the (wins, age) record this gate
;   reads, so the route's own trace feeds the composting decision. Two floors, two protections: anomaly-band's
;   floor keeps a just-seen reading from being flagged anomalous; forget-stale's min-age floor keeps a
;   just-interned prototype from being dropped before it has had its fair chance — the same "protect the fresh"
;   move, one on a value, one on a record.
;
; HONEST LANE (lc-honest-lane):
;   this is a hard two-condition membership, not a graded "stale-ness score". A record one win under the
;   ceiling is flagged exactly like one with zero wins; a record one query past min-age is judged exactly like
;   an ancient one. Membership is exact; SEVERITY (how overdue to drop, how cold the prototype) is not this
;   recipe's claim. That is the right primitive for a fair-chance composting gate (has this had its chance and
;   still not earned its place?); a continuous win-rate RANKING — order the survivors by wins-per-opportunity —
;   is a later brick, the way a deviation score is anomaly-band's later brick. The fair-chance floor is load-
;   bearing honesty: a young prototype is NEVER stale, however few its wins, because it has not yet been given
;   the queries to prove itself; dropping it would be punishing absence of evidence as evidence of absence.
;
; CAVEAT, named not hidden:
;   the gate only knows wins and age — it cannot see WHY a prototype never won. A genuinely valuable prototype
;   for an input distribution that simply has not arrived yet will read stale once it ages past min-age with no
;   wins; forget-stale measures realized recognition, not latent worth, so a rare-but-true shape needs either a
;   generous min-age or a caller that protects it by other means. And WHERE min-age sits and how low max-wins
;   reaches is the caller's judgement: a tiny min-age composts prototypes before they could prove out; a huge
;   one lets dead weight linger. forget-stale makes the chosen gate's boundary exact and three-way-identical;
;   choosing min-age and max-wins — how patient the body is before it forgets — is the caller's lane, an honest one.
;
; KIN: nearest-shape.form (the interning twin — admit a prototype to learn; forget-stale drops one to compost) ·
;   classifier-eval.form (the same division-free two-count gate, pointed at promotion instead of forgetting) ·
;   anomaly-band.form (the fair-chance floor mirrors anomaly's boundary-belongs-to-normal protection of the fresh) ·
;   recognition-router.form (emits the wins this gate tallies against age) · lc-honest-lane (never won after a
;   fair chance is a decision to compost, never a graded score; the floor protects the just-interned).
;
; LINEAGE:
;   the same recognition memory that nearest-shape grows, here pruned by its own lived record — a prototype's
;   worth is the queries it actually won, judged only after it has had the chances to win them. This is how the
;   substrate stays supple instead of merely accumulating: forgetting is a breath, not a loss, and the body
;   composts what never circulated by NodeID-identical judgement on Go, Rust, and TS.
